title: For Sale:  Remington SP-10
postcontent: I've decided to part with my Remington SP-10 semi-automatic waterfowl shotgun. Had it for years but just don't hunt with it the way I used to, so figure it's time to move it along to someone who will use it. It has the 32" barrel (swings and points like a dream) threaded for screw-in chokes, and currently has the steel full choke tube in place. That is the only choke I have for it, but others can be found. I've only used tungsten shot in this gun and on ducks and geese it's an absolute monster! Nothing else in the marsh sounds like a 10 gauge or hits with the authority of one. One of my duck hunting buds nicknamed this one "The Hammer of God" after it dropped at wounded goose at an absolutely absurd distance. While some may be hesitant to buy into a 10 gauge due to recoil, this one produces only a mighty shove. It's nowhere near as violent as any of the 3-1/2" 12 gauge guns I've fired. Price is $800 FIRM and I'll leave this ad up for a week or two, then it's off to gunbroker.com where it will fetch substantially more.

title: For Sale:  Wichita 6mm PPC Benchrest Rifle
postcontent: This is a Wichita (1375 action) 6mm PPC benchrest rifle I took in trade almost two years ago and it has sat in the safe ever since. Wichita PPC right bolt/left port action, heavy stainless 6mm PPC barrel (I have no idea who built this rifle or who the barrel maker is) in what appears to be immaculate condition both inside and out. Rifle has what is clearly a 2 oz. BR-grade trigger and if I had to guess, I'd say it's a Jewell. One of the cleanest, lightest, and most crisp triggers I've ever felt. Flawless custom-machined 1" scope rings and bases. Stock is finished in what i'd describe as a midnight blue/black motor oil metal flake paint of automotive grade. Additional photos available on request. Wichita 1375 stripped actions commonly sell in the $650-700 range, so this package deal is a steal! $800 firm. The only trade I'd be really interested in would be a Savage 112 Target Magnum (.338 Lapua), although other especially interesting long-range rifles may be considered.Update: This rifle's chamber neck diameter is .262" as I suspected. This is the most common neck diameter used by benchrest shooters to obtain the near-legendary accuracy the 6PPC is noted for. If you're looking at this ad, you probably already know this necessitates a set of semi-custom dies and neck turning of the brass to match this chamber dimension. As the chamber dimensions match what most competitors are shooting, getting set up to load for this rifle should be a relatively straightforward and reasonably economical affair. Pair that with a decent scope and you should be ready for the range.

The Ruger Mark III Hunter carries on the legacy of the Mark I and II while incorporating a host of engineering improvements.
